{"body":"Issue #33 and the PR description say the Python domain model should align to the C# shape (Property has an Address property and the JSON uses that nested object). Here the SQLModel `Property` flattens `street/city/province/postal_code/country` onto the root model, and `Address` is not referenced by `Property`, so the model doesn’t actually match the C# `Property`/`Address` shape (see `src/AgentOrchestrator/PropertyDatabase.cs:15,28-35`). This mismatch will make it harder to keep parity when `search_properties` becomes a tool (and when returning results in the same shape as the seed JSON/C# tool output).","id":3609200528,"line":27,"path":"src/python_agent_orchestrator/src/python_agent_orchestrator/models.py"}
{"body":"`search_properties()` returns `Property.model_dump()` directly, which (with the current model) yields snake_case keys and a flattened address. If the intent is parity with the C# demo and the seed JSON shape from `src/AgentOrchestrator/Data/Properties/*.json`, consider returning results in the same JSON shape (camelCase + nested `address`) so tool consumers don’t need to special-case Python vs C# output.","id":3609200545,"line":91,"path":"src/python_agent_orchestrator/src/python_agent_orchestrator/property_database.py"}
{"body":"The tests currently assert against flattened, snake_case fields (e.g., `result[\"city\"]`). If Phase 3.2 is meant to match the C# `Property`/`Address` JSON shape (nested `address`, camelCase names), these assertions will need to be updated to validate that shape instead (e.g., `result[\"address\"][\"city\"]`, `result[\"keyFeatures\"]`, etc.).","id":3609200558,"line":36,"path":"src/python_agent_orchestrator/tests/test_property_database.py"}

